SC, Program Graph Structure Description A program graph is a directed graph used to represent the control flow of a program. For the above Java implementation of a triangle judgment program, its program graph nodes and edges can be described as follows: Node 1: Program start, receive inputs a, b, c. Node 2: Determine if a is within the range [1, 200]. If not, output "The value of a is not within the allowed range." and end the program; if so, proceed to Node 3. Node 3: Determine if b is within the range [1, 200]. If not, output "The value of b is not within the allowed range." and end the program; if so, proceed to Node 4. Node 4: Determine if c is within the range [1, 200]. If not, output "The value of c is not within the allowed range." and end the program; if so, proceed to Node 5. Node 5: Determine if the triangle side length conditions are met (a < b + c and b < a + c and c < a + b). If not, output "Not a triangle" and end the program; if so, proceed to Node 6. Node 6: Determine if it is an equilateral triangle (a == b && b == c). If so, output "Equilateral triangle" and end the program; if not, proceed to Node 7. Node 7: Determine if it is an isosceles triangle (a == b || a == c || b == c). If so, output "Isosceles triangle" and end the program; if not, output "Scalene triangle" and end the program.
